The majority of these notes are written at the foot of the pagos of the MS, and eonsist of additions to the text of the Eulogium, collected from many different sources, often contemporary with the events described, and generally chosen with care and judgment. It becomes a question of some interest to determine whether these additions were in whole or in part transcribed from the text of some original of the Eulogium posterior to the autograph, or are, as they at first sight appear to be, independent notes made to the text of B. by three different readers of that MS.
